<br>
Acts of war will always be heinous.  War should never be candy coated.<br>
<br>
If parents are unable to ship their children to daycare or school, they are probably unable to go to work in a factory or an office building.  No work means no economic output, which further reduces the size of the war machine that can be supported.<br>
<br>
Have you ever played a real-time strategy game?  There is a reason that economy output is directly linked to war capacity.<br>
<br>
Reducing the economic output of the opposition is an excellent method for reducing their capacity for war.  It may be the best method to win a war while preserving the resources available to the victor.  If both sides only fight a purely &quot;military&quot; campaign, then it is a contest to force the opposition to exahust their resources first.<br>
<br>
Purely military campaigns are much more brutal, on a humanitarian scale, than economic ones. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#989dca><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub41.ezboard.com/bvazaellecommunitycenter.showUserPublicProfile?gid=ammelen>Ammelen</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>I Live Here</span><br>  Posts: 2057<br> <font color=#FFFFFF>(9/19/03 5:49 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub41.ezboard.com/fvazaellecommunitycenterfrm30.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=195.topic&index=24>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Warfare vs Terrorism</span><hr size=1> That connection is very, very distant.  I'm not saying it isn't there, because I agree it has some *small* effect on the ability of a country to make war.  However, there are many, many targets that would be much more effective in reducing the ability of Israel to make war on the Palestinians.  The fact that these are not chosen shows that the intent is not to weaken Israel's ability to make war, as your connection would suggest, but rather to hurt innocent people and cause pain with very minimal military gain.<br>
