<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>If you choose to bomb the university just to hurt innocent people, even though another target nearby would have a greater effect on your enemy to make war, then that would be terrorism.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--> But that doesn't happen in real life.  No group or army or general would allocate resources to destroy a target when they can allocate the same resources to destroy a different target that has a greater impact on the outcome of the war.  That's a bizarre type of altruism that only happens in thought experiements.<br>
<br>
In the case of the Palestinians, the aim is not a military victory.  They seek to instill enough fear and despair in the Israeli population that the Israeli government will give in and make concessions.  In that case, bombing a university, or a bus, is MUCH more effective than bombing a tank or military barracks.<br>
