I think it's wrong too, but I'm not talking about wrong or right. I'm saying that in wartime countries will never take much heed to Geneva conventions - they only abide by them, if they have the luxury to do so. If abiding by them means losing the war, or the reverse, not abiding means you will get a decisive advantage, every country will be willing to break the rules. Winning the war is all that matters.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>Generally, I think this is because the crimes of the Nazis were so much more horrible than anything else. They were clear aggressors and clearly at fault.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
Ohhhhh, now we're getting somewhere ! So terrorism is acceptable if your side has righteous goals ! Now we only have to define right and wrong ! <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START ;) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/wink.gif ALT=";)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END--> <br>
<br>
Okay, joking aside, what I meant was that there is often a very thin line between freedom fighters and terrorists (not Hamas though)<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>Those are not innocent people though. Those are terrorists. They are mostly Al Qaeda members. The key difference is targeting the innocent and targeting those responsible for war.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
I'm not disputing their guilt. Geneva has nothing to do with innocence. I'm not disputing that the targetting of civilians, just to cause fear is a despicable act. I'm trying to point out that people's perspective on what is allowed in wartime differs greatly depending on whose side you're on.<br>
<br>
As much as it disgusts me, it can be argued that without terrorist attacks, Israel wouldn't even think about negotiating.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>I don't think this is true actually. The United States and many other countries have avoided certain practices that could be beneficial to them as a matter of conscience.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
But only because they have the luxury to do so. Our morals would get out of the door quick if the sovereignity (sp) of your country is at stake. <p>---------------<br>
